<subSubSection id="D3E79686FFFAFFB9FF935494A47CF9C6" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" type="description">
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF935494A4D8FCCB" blockId="5.[111,649,755,1320]" box="[113,412,755,781]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">
DESCRIPTION OF 
<typeStatus id="44467BAFFFFAFFB9FECF549FA4D8FCCB" box="[301,412,760,779]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">HOLOTYPE</typeStatus>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF935575A454FAC8" blockId="5.[111,649,755,1320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">
Length: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FF2E5575A460FCED" box="[204,292,786,813]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="8.2">8.2 mm</quantity>
; length of elytra: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FE3C5575A772FCED" box="[478,566,786,813]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="5.9">5.9 mm</quantity>
; width: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FF935555A58FFC8D" box="[113,203,818,845]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
. Body surface brown with greenish shine. Head and antenna as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FE615535A746FCAB" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[387,514,849,875]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FE615535A746FCAB" box="[387,514,849,875]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; eyes small, ratio of diameter/interocular width: 0.58. Antennomeres 3-5 not fused; club a little longer than the remaining antennomeres combined. Pronotum and scutellum as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FEAC55B6A48FFC2A" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[334,459,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FEAC55B6A48FFC2A" box="[334,459,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, except the basal marginal line of pronotum being more distinct and widely interrupted medially and its surface bearing a single long seta on the center of each pronotal half. Elytra as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FF085237A426FBA9" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[234,354,1103,1129]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FF085237A426FBA9" box="[234,354,1103,1129]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Metacoxa and pygidium as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FF6C5208A44DFB48" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[142,265,1134,1160]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FF6C5208A44DFB48" box="[142,265,1134,1160]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Ratio of length of metepisternum/ metacoxa: 1/1.89. Legs as in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FE4E52E8A76DFB68" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[428,553,1166,1192]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FE4E52E8A76DFB68" box="[428,553,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; ratio of metatibial width/length: 1/4.17, medial face of metatibia with one or two punctures beside the dorsal margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF6A536AA4CEFAE8" blockId="5.[111,649,755,1320]" box="[136,394,1293,1320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">
Aedeagus: 
<figureCitation id="03C6D988FFFAFFB9FF19536AA40BFAE8" box="[251,335,1293,1320]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,1277,1294]" captionTargetBox="[490,671,1083,1223]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 1. — A, Distribution of the species of Emphania (Emphania erichsoni n. sp.could not be localized due to insufficient label information “Madagascar”),the habitus of the type species E.metallica (Blanchard,1850) is shown (not scaled) in upper left corner;B-D, E. metallica (Blanchard, 1850) (lectotype); E-G, E. lacroixi n. sp. (holotype); B, E, aedeagus, left side lateral views; C, F, aedeagus, dorsal views; D, G, aedeagus, right side lateral views. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4525863" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4525863/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">Figure 1</figureCitation>
E-G.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF93532AA5A3FAA5" blockId="5.[111,647,1357,1542]" box="[113,231,1357,1383]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">VARIATION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF93530BA47CF9C6" blockId="5.[111,647,1357,1542]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">
Length: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FF28530BA408FA47" box="[202,332,1388,1415]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.05" metricValueMax="9.9" metricValueMin="8.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="9.05" valueMax="9.9" valueMin="8.2">8.2-9.9 mm</quantity>
; length of elytra: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FDE2530BA7C6FA47" box="[512,642,1388,1415]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.05" metricValueMax="6.2" metricValueMin="5.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="6.05" valueMax="6.2" valueMin="5.9">5.9-6.2 mm</quantity>
; width: 
<quantity id="5C0568E8FFFAFFB9FF5B53EBA47EFA67" box="[185,314,1420,1447]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.75" metricValueMax="5.3" metricValueMin="4.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" unit="mm" value="4.75" valueMax="5.3" valueMin="4.2">4.2-5.3 mm</quantity>
. The colour varies from blackish green to reddish purple. The female has the antennal club slightly shorter and the punctures on pygidium are very indistinct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D3E79686FFFAFFB9FF93504CA14BFEF2" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9B42C50DFFFAFFB9FF93504CA14BFEF2" blockId="5.[111,647,1579,1700]" lastBlockId="5.[675,1210,216,306]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">
REMARKS The species is very similar in external morphology to 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FF8D500DA5A0F943" baseAuthorityName="Blanchard" baseAuthorityYear="1850" box="[111,228,1641,1667]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Heptomera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="metallica">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FF8D500DA5A0F943" box="[111,228,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. metallica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and may externally only be distinguished by the unfused antennomeres 3-5. The shape of parameres provides more confidence for separating both taxa; parameres are longer in 
<taxonomicName id="5CFDBE8EFFFAFFB9FBF3569FA13FFED1" authority="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi, 2008" authorityName="Ahrens &amp; Fabrizi" authorityYear="2008" box="[1041,1147,247,273]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Emphania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacroixi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="A989191FFFFAFFB9FBF3569FA13FFED1" box="[1041,1147,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="922">E. lacroixi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B2BAA464FFFAFFB9FB62569FA1FEFED3" box="[1152,1210,248,275]" pageId="5" pageNumber="922" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
with a widely curved apical hook.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
